<p>I wrote the following code and I'm not 100% sure why it is working.<br/> Fiddle : <a href="https://jsfiddle.net/mcnc5vk4/1/" rel="nofollow">https://jsfiddle.net/mcnc5vk4/1/</a></p>  <pre><code>jQuery(document).ready(function($) {  function getNavLinks() {     /*     var contentIDs = ["id-1", "id-2", "id-3"];      for(var i = 0; i &lt; contentIDs.length; i++){         var contentID = contentIDs[i];     }     */     var contentID;      $(".sidebar .nav a").click(function() {         var navLinkAttr = $(this).attr("href");             navLinkAttr = navLinkAttr.substring(1)          if( jQuery.inArray(navLinkAttr, contentID) ) {             var contentBorderLeft = $(".blog .item &gt; div#" + navLinkAttr).addClass("content-border-left");              setTimeout(function() {                 $(contentBorderLeft).removeClass("content-border-left");             }, 900);          } else{             console.log("it does not work");         }      }); };  getNavLinks();  }); </code></pre>  <p><strong>What it does is:</strong><br/> I have a left sidebar with a navigation which links to some anchors in the content.</p>  <p>When you click on a nav item the window scrolls down to the anchor in the content. The element which is linked on gets a left border to visualize the active element. So far so good.</p>  <p><strong>Ideas for implementation</strong><br/> My idea was to get the <em>href</em> of the navigation elements and compare them with the IDs of the content elements. Then add a <em>class</em> with some styling to the content element and remove it after a few seconds.</p>  <p><strong>Problem</strong><br/> Just for development I created an array (contentIDs) with all the IDs of the content elements. After some testing I noticed that the array is not needed. So I uncommented it and created a emty variable <em>contentID</em>.</p>  <p>I have no idea where the code gets all the needed IDs from, to compare them with the <em>hrefs</em> of the nav elements.</p>  <h2>Edit</h2>  <p>I think it has something to do with <strong>jQuery.inArray(navLinkAttr, contentID)</strong> in my if statement.</p>  <p>But how is it possible that <em>.inArray</em> can search for the navigation href (navLinkAttr) inside contentID, when this is empty?</p>